---
name: gh-commit-content
description: Safe patterns for creating GitHub issues and git commits with multi-line or quote-containing content. Use this skill whenever creating GH issues (gh issue create), editing issues (gh issue edit), creating PRs (gh pr create), or committing with multi-line messages. Shell quoting with heredocs or inline strings frequently breaks when content contains single quotes, double quotes, backticks, or dollar signs — this skill avoids those pitfalls entirely by using temp files.
---

# GitHub Content Authoring: Issues, PRs, and Commits

Shell quoting breaks silently when issue bodies or commit messages contain quotes, backticks, template literals, or dollar signs — all common in technical content. The fix is simple: always write content to a temp file first, then pass the file to the CLI tool.

## Why temp files instead of heredocs

Heredocs (`<<'EOF'`) handle most quoting, but still fail when content contains unmatched quotes or certain bash metacharacters. Temp files are universally safe regardless of content.

## Creating GitHub Issues

```bash
# 1. Write the body to a temp file (use Write tool, not echo/cat heredoc)
#    File: /tmp/gh-issue-<descriptive-name>.md

# 2. Create the issue using --body-file
gh issue create \
  --repo owner/repo \
  --title "Issue title here" \
  --label "bug,enhancement" \
  --body-file /tmp/gh-issue-<descriptive-name>.md

# 3. Clean up
rm -f /tmp/gh-issue-<descriptive-name>.md
```

Use the Write tool to create the temp file — this avoids any shell interpretation of the content.

## Editing GitHub Issues

```bash
# 1. Write the updated body to a temp file
#    File: /tmp/gh-issue-edit-<descriptive-name>.md

# 2. Edit the issue using --body-file
gh issue edit <number> \
  --repo owner/repo \
  --body-file /tmp/gh-issue-edit-<descriptive-name>.md

# 3. Clean up
rm -f /tmp/gh-issue-edit-<descriptive-name>.md
```

## Creating Pull Requests

```bash
# 1. Write the PR body to a temp file
#    File: /tmp/gh-pr-<descriptive-name>.md

# 2. Create the PR using --body-file
gh pr create \
  --title "PR title here" \
  --body-file /tmp/gh-pr-<descriptive-name>.md

# 3. Clean up
rm -f /tmp/gh-pr-<descriptive-name>.md
```

## Creating Git Commits

```bash
# 1. Write the commit message to a temp file
cat > "$TMPDIR/msg.txt" << 'EOF'
type(scope): short description

Longer explanation of the change, which can contain `backticks`,
"double quotes", 'single quotes', $variables, and any other content
without shell escaping issues.
EOF

# 2. Commit using -F (file)
git commit -F "$TMPDIR/msg.txt"

# 3. Clean up
rm -f "$TMPDIR/msg.txt"
```

For commit messages, `$TMPDIR` is preferred over `/tmp/` since it uses the OS temp directory.

Note: Single-line commit messages without special characters can safely use `git commit -m "message"` — the temp file pattern is for multi-line messages or messages with quotes/backticks.

## Cleanup

Always remove temp files after the command succeeds. If the command fails, keep the temp file so the content can be inspected or retried.

```bash
# Pattern: create, use, clean up
TMPFILE="/tmp/gh-issue-$(date +%s).md"
# ... write content to $TMPFILE ...
gh issue create --body-file "$TMPFILE" && rm -f "$TMPFILE"
```

## Common Pitfalls

- **Inline `--body` with heredoc**: Fails when body contains unmatched single quotes or `$(...)` expressions
- **`-m` with complex messages**: Shell interprets `$`, backticks, and quotes before git sees them
- **Process substitution (`<(...)`)**: Fails when the inner command has quoting issues — same problem, just nested
- **Forgetting cleanup**: Temp files accumulate in `/tmp/` — always clean up after successful use
